ask: cdx control_bridge strcpy -> strscpy on userspace ifname (audit B6 / P1.05)

AUDIT-cdx P1.05: control_bridge.c::cdx_l2_bridge_add() copies the
input/output interface names supplied by the FPP command channel
(ultimately userspace via FCI) into the bounded l2flow_entry buffers
with strcpy() — no NUL-termination guarantee, no length bound:

  strcpy(&l2flow_entry->out_ifname[0], pcmd->output_name);
  strcpy(&l2flow_entry->in_ifname[0],  pcmd->input_name);

If pcmd->output_name or pcmd->input_name is exactly IFNAMSIZ bytes
without an embedded NUL (the netlink wire format does not require
NUL-terminated strings), strcpy() walks past the source until it
finds a zero byte somewhere on the heap — leaking adjacent kmalloc
chunks into the destination, or worse, overflowing the destination
itself if the source is longer than the destination.

Fix: switch to strscpy() with sizeof(dst). strscpy() always
NUL-terminates and never reads past the source bound; truncation
silently produces a shorter-than-IFNAMSIZ ifname which subsequent
get_onif_by_name()-style lookups will simply miss (returning
ERR_UNKNOWN_INTERFACE) — the safe failure mode.

This is the head of the cdx D7 mirror sweep tracked in the audit
report; the ~12 other strcpy/sscanf%s sites in cdx_mc_query.c,
control_ipv4.c, control_pppoe.c, control_tunnel.c, control_vlan.c
and dpa_cfg.c are deferred to B6b (out-of-scope mirror sweep) once
the canonical pattern is validated by CI here.

No ABI / UAPI delta. No kernel-side delta.

Audit-batch: B6
Audit-finding: AUDIT-cdx P1.05--- a/cdx/control_bridge.c
+++ b/cdx/control_bridge.c
@@ -359,8 +359,10 @@
 				ackstatus = ERR_UNKNOWN_INTERFACE;
 				goto func_ret;
 			}
-			strcpy(&l2flow_entry->out_ifname[0], pcmd->output_name);
-			strcpy(&l2flow_entry->in_ifname[0], pcmd->input_name);
+			strscpy(&l2flow_entry->out_ifname[0], pcmd->output_name,
+				sizeof(l2flow_entry->out_ifname));
+			strscpy(&l2flow_entry->in_ifname[0], pcmd->input_name,
+				sizeof(l2flow_entry->in_ifname));
 			memcpy(&l2flow_entry->l2flow, &l2flow, sizeof(struct L2Flow));
